Export: promoting a variable to the environment.

A plain assignment, name equals value, creates a shell variable, and only the current shell can see it. To make a variable visible to the commands you launch, you use export. You can export a variable you've already made, or you can assign and export it in a single line.

Here's how to verify the difference. A plain shell variable shows up when you run set, but not when you run env. An exported variable shows up in both.

Now the key rule, and it's one that trips people up: inheritance flows one way only. When you launch a program, it receives a copy of the environment. Any changes that child makes to its own environment never flow back to the parent. This is exactly why a variable you set inside a script doesn't stick around after the script finishes. The script ran in its own shell, and when that shell exited, it took its environment with it.

And that, in turn, is why shell startup files matter so much. Files like dot-bashrc and dot-profile are read every time a shell starts, and they typically export the variables you want available in every single session. We'll cover those files in detail in module six.
